## Part 2: Apex Standards

_When Apex is required (after exhausting declarative options), follow these conventions._

### 10. Naming Conventions

**Verify:** Design — class and controller names appear in design docs when Apex is specified.

| Element          | Convention                 | Example                      |
| ---------------- | -------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| Class            | UpperCamelCase             | `AccountTriggerHandler`      |
| Method           | lowerCamelCase, verb-first | `processAccount()`           |
| Variable         | lowerCamelCase             | `billingAccounts`            |
| Constant         | UPPER_SNAKE_CASE           | `MAX_RETRY_COUNT`            |
| Trigger          | `{Object}Trigger`          | `AccountTrigger`             |
| Trigger Handler  | `{Object}TriggerHandler`   | `AccountTriggerHandler`      |
| Test Class       | `Test_{ClassName}`         | `Test_AccountTriggerHandler` |
| Controller       | `{Name}Controller`         | `CommunitiesLoginController` |
| Invocable Action | Descriptive verb phrase    | `InvocableScheduleFlow`      |

### 11. Formatting

**Verify:** Build — code formatting only exists in source files.

- **2-space indentation**, no tabs
- Opening brace on the same line as the statement
- Single blank line between methods
- Explicit access modifiers on every class and method (`public`, `private`, `global` only when required)
- **`with sharing` by default**; `without sharing` only with documented justification; `inherited sharing` for utility classes

### 12. Class Headers

**Verify:** Build — class headers only exist in source files.

JSDoc-style block comment at the top of every class:

```apex
/**
 * @author      Developer Name
 * @description Handles Account trigger logic for risk flag evaluation
 * @testClass   Test_AccountTriggerHandler
 */
public with sharing class AccountTriggerHandler {
```

Required tags: `@author`, `@description`, `@testClass`. For Invocable classes, add `@inputs` and `@outputs` describing flow-facing parameters.

### 13. Trigger Handler Pattern

**Verify:** Design — trigger framework usage is specified when Apex triggers are in scope.

One trigger per object. The trigger file is a thin delegate — no logic:

```apex
trigger AccountTrigger on Account(before insert, after insert, after update) {
  AccountTriggerHandler.getInstance().fire();
}
```

The handler class uses a **singleton with boolean recursion guards**:

```apex
public with sharing class AccountTriggerHandler {
  private static AccountTriggerHandler instance;
  private static Boolean isBeforeExecuting = false;
  private static Boolean isAfterExecuting = false;

  public static AccountTriggerHandler getInstance() {
    instance = (instance == null) ? new AccountTriggerHandler() : instance;
    return instance;
  }

  public void fire() {
    if (Trigger.isBefore) {
      if (!isBeforeExecuting) {
        isBeforeExecuting = true;
        if (Trigger.isInsert)
          beforeInsert();
        if (Trigger.isUpdate)
          beforeUpdate();
        if (Trigger.isDelete)
          beforeDelete();
        isBeforeExecuting = false;
      }
    }
    if (Trigger.isAfter) {
      if (!isAfterExecuting) {
        isAfterExecuting = true;
        if (Trigger.isInsert)
          afterInsert();
        if (Trigger.isUpdate)
          afterUpdate();
        if (Trigger.isDelete)
          afterDelete();
        if (Trigger.isUndelete)
          afterUndelete();
        isAfterExecuting = false;
      }
    }
  }

  private void beforeInsert() {
    /* logic here */
  }
  private void beforeUpdate() {
    /* logic here */
  }
  private void beforeDelete() {
    /* logic here */
  }
  private void afterInsert() {
    /* logic here */
  }
  private void afterUpdate() {
    /* logic here */
  }
  private void afterDelete() {
    /* logic here */
  }
  private void afterUndelete() {
    /* logic here */
  }
}
```

### 14. SOQL Standards

**Verify:** Build — SOQL patterns only exist in source code.

```apex
List<Account> accounts = [
    SELECT Id, Name, Risk_Score__c
    FROM Account
    WHERE Status__c = :targetStatus
    AND CreatedDate >= :startDate
    ORDER BY Name ASC
    LIMIT 200
];
```

- Keywords **UPPERCASE**: `SELECT`, `FROM`, `WHERE`, `AND`, `ORDER BY`, `LIMIT`
- `Id` always first in field list
- One clause per line
- **Bind variables** over string concatenation (prevents SOQL injection)
- No SOQL in loops
- Use **`WITH USER_MODE`** or **`WITH SECURITY_ENFORCED`** for CRUD/FLS enforcement

### 15. Security

**Verify:** Design — security model (sharing, FLS enforcement, user mode) must be specified for Apex components.

- **Always declare sharing explicitly** — omitting it is a security anti-pattern
- **Prefer User Mode operations**: `WITH USER_MODE` in SOQL, `insert as user`, `Database.insert(record, AccessLevel.USER_MODE)`
- Fallback: `WITH SECURITY_ENFORCED` in SOQL (throws `QueryException` if user lacks access)
- Fallback: `Security.stripInaccessible()` for graceful degradation on DML
- **`@AuraEnabled` classes must use `with sharing`**
- `without sharing` requires a comment explaining why system-level access is needed

### 16. Apex Test Standards

**Verify:** Build — test structure and coverage only exist in source code.

```apex
@IsTest(seeAllData=false)
private class Test_AccountTriggerHandler {
  @TestSetup
  static void setupData() {
    // Create all test data here — never rely on org data
  }

  @IsTest
  static void test_Success_Single() {
    Test.startTest();
    // invoke the code under test
    Test.stopTest();

    System.assertEquals(expected, actual, 'Descriptive assertion message');
  }
}
```

- `@IsTest` annotation (not the deprecated `testmethod` keyword)
- `private` access modifier on test classes
- `seeAllData=false` explicit (even though it's the default)
- `@TestSetup` for shared test data
- `Test.startTest()` / `Test.stopTest()` wrapping async and governor-sensitive operations
- **Assertion messages required** on every `System.assertEquals` / `System.assert`
- Test categories: **positive**, **negative**, **bulk** (200+ records), **permission** (`System.runAs()`)
- **90% coverage per class** (75% is the Salesforce deployment floor, not our target)
- `HttpCalloutMock` inner classes for callout testing — never use `Test.isRunningTest()` branching

### 17. Flow Testing Standards

**Verify:** Design — test strategy (which flows get native tests, coverage targets) specified in design doc. Build — actual test metadata.

- **lightning-flow-scanner** must pass with zero errors before commit (all flow types). Already installed as an SF CLI plugin (`sf flow scan --directory force-app/main/default/flows`).
- **Native Flow Tests** (record-triggered flows):
  - **Required** for any record-triggered flow built or modified by Claude — test created in the same session as the flow
  - **Recommended** for manually-built record-triggered flows (Claude can assist)
  - Not applicable to screen, scheduled/batch, or subflows (native tests don't support them)
  - Tests are deployable SFDX metadata (`FlowTest` type, `flowtests/` directory)
  - Each test should cover: happy path, key decision branches, boundary conditions
- **Flow descriptions** should document test scenarios (what was tested, expected behavior)

### 18. Anti-Patterns

**Verify:** Build — anti-patterns can only be detected in actual code/metadata.

Do not:

- Use `global` access modifier unless required by managed package interface or `@InvocableMethod`
- Hard-code IDs (applies to both Apex and Flows)
- Put SOQL or DML inside loops
- Leave `System.debug` statements in committed code
- Use the deprecated `testmethod` keyword
- Use `@isTest(SeeAllData=true)`
- Use `Test.isRunningTest()` for conditional branching — use mocks instead
- Write dummy code (`i++`) solely to inflate coverage metrics
- Omit the sharing keyword on any class

